The paper focuses on the design and development of an online social skills development interface for teenagers with autism spectrum disorder (ASD), which involves the use of a virtual conversational agent. This falls under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC), which is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of automated feedback and dialogue generation using hidden Markov models and schema-driven dialogue managers, which falls under the categories of natural language processing (cs.CL) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper discusses the design considerations for the interface, which includes personalization and engagement, which falls under the categories of cyberpsychology (cs.CY) and machine learning (cs.LG).
